\newpage 

\subsection{Experience determining $C_{p}$}
\lhead{5.2 Experience determining $C_{p}$}
We are looking to determine the thrust coefficient of the propeller $C_{p}$. We know that the thrust generated by a rotating propeller follows the law: 
$$F=\rho C_{t} \dot{ \beta }^{2}D^{4}$$
\begin{tabular}{ll}
-- $\dot{ \beta }$ : Propeller rotation speed & 
-- $\rho$ : Volumic mass\\
-- $D$ : Propeller's diameter &
-- $C_{t}$ : Thrust coefficient\\
\end{tabular}\\
\\ Hence, if we manage to both know the thrust generated and the angular speed of the propeller then we can deduce the coefficient $C_{t}$. The method we are going to use is to use the flexibility of a beam that will serve as a stress sensor.\\
\\
We will use a DC motor, whose rate of rotation is going to vary according to the tension input to do several measurements.
This motor will be imbedded into an aluminium plate, then we will do several measurements of the thrust generated, thanks to a sensor measuring the deformation at the bottom of the plate, and the rate of rotation, thanks to a tachymeter.\\
\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=13cm]{/Users/bozelremy/Pictures/Saved Pictures/Schema.png}
\caption{Experience set up}
\end{figure}
\hspace{18cm}
-- $F$ : The force generated by the rotation of the DC motor we are going to apply to measure the deformation $\varepsilon$.\\
However, to know the thrust generated, we will need to know the link between the thrust and the deformation. It will require to do several tests with known weights. We should obtain a linear graph (which means $F=\lambda \varepsilon $) as long as the deformation remains in the elastic domain.\\
\\
Now that we know the relation between $F$ and $\varepsilon$ we can proceed to the tests with the DC motor.
Since we have established that $F=\rho C_{t}\dot{\beta }^{2}D^{4}$, we know that if we plot the graph $F(\dot{ \beta }^{2})$, it should be linear :
$$F=C_{p}\dot{ \beta }^{2}$$
\begin{equation}
C_{p}=\rho C_{t}D^{4}
\end{equation}
